<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06275130 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06275130 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: (Steve Eklund)  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; RACING; MAN; ACCIDENT; DEATH; OBITUARY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  In the days when the flat track ruled motorcycle racing, Steve Eklund was Kingof the Privateers.;   No factory backed the San Jose kid from Mount PleasantHigh School, but during the late 1970s before motocross racing became sopopular, he took on Team Harley-Davidson and all the other motorcycle makerswith his own Harley and beat them.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  STEVE EKLUND, 36, MOTORCYCLE CHAMP  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Obituaries  </MEMO><TEXT>     For 28 weeks every year, Mr. Eklund and his boyhood-buddy mechanic FrankNye would use a barn in Plainfield, Ill., as a home base and make livingexpenses by running in the Wednesday night races at Santa Fe Speedway nearChicago.;   On weekends, they would head out for the grand national pointsraces all over the country in search of the big prize.;   In 1976, Mr. Eklundwas Rookie of the Year on the dirt tracks, finishing fourth in the nationalrankings. He was right there again in 1977 and '78.;   But his year was 1979.Early in the season before his fans at the Santa Clara County Fairgrounds racetrack, he won the San Jose Mile and later the national title.;   At 24, SteveEklund was the best in a business that could support no more than three orfour dozen riders as full-time professionals.;   And nobody could beat him inthe TT steeplechase. He was the all-time winning rider in that most difficultof all dirt track races, with left- and right-hand corners and a jump at 60 to90 mph. The race is rarely run anymore.;   Then came the slump. From 1980 to'82, he won only one grand national race. &quot;I wasn't in the hunt,&quot; he said atthe time; 1983 was better, but not enough, and Mr. Eklund quit full-timeracing in 1984.;   &quot;We came home and decided to get jobs,&quot; said Anne Eklund,whom Mr. Eklund had married in 1979 after his national championship.;   Lifeas a carpenter in San Jose was OK for Mr. Eklund, but he couldn't retireentirely.;   &quot;It's always good to race at home,&quot; said Nye, who now owns hisown firm, Engines Only, which builds motorcycle engines in Campbell. &quot;Thereare those little scrambles, and we'd go out there and ride them.&quot;;   In 1989,after all those years on a Harley, Mr. Eklund found a $12,000 Honda, and hegot the urge again, said his wife. &quot;He got fifth in his first race. It was thefirst time we owned our own bike.&quot;;   Then in the Albuquerque (N.M.) Mile inJune 1990, Mr. Eklund was leading with only five laps to go when he crashed.;  &quot;He went out in style,&quot; Nye said. &quot;He was going to win it. The rest ishistory.&quot;;   The history is 15 months in a coma and, finally, death of severebrain injury Thursday at 36 in a special room built and donated by CraigRogers, a contractor for whom Mr. Eklund had often worked when he wasn'tracing.;   &quot;He was a good finish carpenter,&quot; said Rogers, &quot;pretty much aperfectionist, as he was in racing.&quot;;   When they ran the San Jose Mile at thefairgrounds two weeks ago, a raffle of an uncut sheet of collectors'motorcycle racing cards brought $1,000 and a flood of memories for AnneEklund, who still faces a mountain of medical bills.;   After today's memorialservice, Steven Allan Eklund will be buried in Oak Hill Memorial Park. &quot;Ipicked a spot way up high overlooking the fairgrounds,&quot; she said.; (box)Born:June 20, 1955, San Jose, Calif.; (box)Died: Sept. 26, 1991, San Jose.;(box)Survived by: Wife, the former Anne McCaul of San Jose; parents, Leonardand Eleanor Eklund of San Jose; brothers and sisters, Gary Eklund of Modesto;Sheryl Harkins of Modesto and Bonnie, Rick and Diane Eklund, all ofPleasanton; father- and mother-in-law, Wallace and Lois McCaul of San Jose.;(box)Services: Memorial at 1:30 p.m. today at Oak Hill Funeral Home, Chapel ofthe Oaks, 300 Curtner Ave., San Jose; burial in Oak Hill Memorial Park.;(box)Memorial: Donations may be made to the Steve Eklund Relief Fund at Bankof the West, Pruneyard Towers office, 1999 S. Bascom Ave., Campbell.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911001  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  692  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, October 1, 199100275130,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>